Use of this document

This is a study note for using \(stat\) package for statistical analysis. The topic consist of:

  • Inferential statistical analysis:
  • Regression Analysis:
    • Analysis of residuals.
  • Analysis of variance (ANOVA):
  • Model Selection

Statistical concepts and methods used in the analysis of data. Statistical models. Analysis of single sample, two sample and paired sample data. Simple and multiple linear regression including polynomial regression. Regression diagnostics. Model building. Regression with indicator variables.

1.1 Distribution

Using Historgram and boxplot, four type of quantitative variables for the distribution of a particular set of data can be understand:

  • Shape: Distribution
  • Center: mean or median or mode
  • Spread: variance, quantile
  • Outliers
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(diamonds$price)
boxplot(diamonds$price ~ diamonds$cut)

# subset with criterion===============================================
diamonds$pval <- 2*pnorm(sort(-abs(diamonds$price)))
diamonds$fdr <- p.adjust(diamonds$pval, method='fdr')
signif <- subset(diamonds, fdr < 0.05)
dim(signif)
## [1] 53940    12

Common Statisical Test 

# t test
t.test(diamonds$price,
       paired=FALSE, var.equal = FALSE, conf.level=0.95)

2. Regression Analysis

2.1 Linear Regression

2.1.1 Analysis of Residuals: Assumption of Linear Regression

diamonds.lm1 <- lm(price ~ carat , data=diamonds)
diamonds.lm2 <- lm(price ~ carat + depth, data=diamonds)
diamonds.lm3 <- lm(price ~ carat + depth + table, data=diamonds)
diamonds.lm4 <- lm(price ~ carat + depth + table + cut, data=diamonds)
# Subplot: Diagnosis fro linear model==================================
par(mfrow=c(2,3))
plot(diamonds.lm1, which=1:6)

diamonds$res = resid(diamonds.lm1)
diamonds$res.standard <- rstandard(diamonds.lm1)
diamonds$res.student <- rstudent(diamonds.lm1)
diamonds$dffit <- dffits(diamonds.lm1)
diamonds$cooks.d <- cooks.distance(diamonds.lm1)
# 1. linearity (no lack of fit): Residuals versus fitted values. Fix: add quadratic term 
# 2. Normality: Normal QQ. Fix: log transform, non-parametric test
# 3. homoscedasticity: Scale-Location. Fix: Log transform
# 4. Outlier: Cook's ddistance. Fix: log transform, non-parametric test, remove outlier

#assume, z is either yes (1) or no (0)

default.glm2 <- glm(default ~ balance + income + student, family = "binomial", data = default)
#summmay of glm
#deviance residuals (a type of residual that makes sense for Yes/No or count data)

#two deviance values and the AIC statistic for the fitted model.

2.3 Diagnosis

Correlation Coefficient to Coefficient of Determinant

# Regression diagnostics ============================================
#if the diamonds.lm1 is the best fit
diamonds.n <- nrow(diamonds)
diamonds.sse0 <- sum(resid(diamonds.lm1) ^2)
#AIC
AIC(diamonds.lm1, k = 2)
## [1] 945466.5
diamonds.lm1.AIC <- diamonds.n + diamonds.n * log(2*pi) + diamonds.n * log(diamonds.sse0/diamonds.n) + 2 * (1+1)
#BIC
BIC(diamonds.lm1)
## [1] 945493.2
AIC(diamonds.lm1, k=log(diamonds.n))
## [1] 945493.2
diamonds.lm1.BIC <- diamonds.n + diamonds.n * log(2*pi) + diamonds.n * log(diamonds.sse0/diamonds.n) + log(diamonds.n)*(1+1)
library(car)
#calculate vif
vif(diamonds.lm3)
##    carat    depth    table 
## 1.042039 1.104275 1.141032
#plot residual and cook's D against observation
plot(diamonds.lm3,4)

#outlier, sr>1.96
sresid <- rstudent(diamonds.lm3)
#influent point, cook.d >1
cooks.d <- cooks.distance(diamonds.lm3)
nobs <- length(sresid)
plot(1:nobs, sresid)

plot(1:nobs, cooks.d)

#calculate the PRESS statistic
#out-of-sample residual
pres <- resid(diamonds.lm3)/sqrt(1-lm.influence(diamonds.lm3)$hat)
#PRESS statistic
press <- sum(pres^2)
#rMSEP
sqrt(press/length(pres))
## [1] 1526.137

3. Analysis of variance (ANOVA)

#type I (sequential) SS and tests, H0: equal group mean
anova(diamonds.lm1)

# diagnoasis for ANOVA for equal variance by groups==================
res.aov<-aov(price ~ color, data=diamonds)
summary(res.aov)
##                Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## color           6 2.685e+10 4.475e+09   290.2 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   53933 8.316e+11 1.542e+07                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
plot(predict(diamonds.lm1),resid(diamonds.lm1))

# H0: same mean, with assumption of no equal variance
oneway.test(price ~ color, data = diamonds)
## 
##  One-way analysis of means (not assuming equal variances)
## 
## data:  price and color
## F = 280.55, num df = 6, denom df = 18316, p-value < 2.2e-16
# Homogeneity of Variance Plot (leveneTest: H0=equal variance)
library(car)
leveneTest(price ~ color, data = diamonds)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = median)
##          Df F value    Pr(>F)    
## group     6  219.12 < 2.2e-16 ***
##       53933                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
library(HH)
hovPlot(price ~ color,data=diamonds)

plot(res.aov, 1)

# Normality-Shapiro-Wilk test: H0=normality of residual
aov_residuals <- residuals(object = res.aov)
shapiro.test(x = aov_residuals[1:3000]) # sample size must be between 3 and 5000
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  aov_residuals[1:3000]
## W = 0.87434, p-value < 2.2e-16
plot(res.aov, 2)

# After ANOVA: Parirwise comparision===================================
#fully parirwise comparision (Tukey Honest Significant Differences)
TukeyHSD(res.aov)
#Mean, SE and confidence interval for each group, forcus on factor 'cut'
#reference grid
diamonds.emm <- emmeans::emmeans(diamonds.lm4, ~ carat + depth + table| cut)
#mean and 95% condence intervals for each group
plot(diamonds.emm)
diamonds.pairs <- pairs(diamonds.emm)
#specific pairwise comparison , such as: residual_trt1=mean.trt1-mean
diamonds.pairs <- emmeans::contrast(diamonds.emm, 
                           list(baseline=c(1,-1,0)
                                #any = c(1, -1/2, -1/2),
                                #linear = c(residual_trt1,residual_trt2,residual_trt3)
                                ))
#summary give CI and T-test by infer() and  with adjust=
summary(diamonds.pairs, infer=c(T,T), adjust='bonferroni')
#adjust= tukey, bonferroni, none, scheffe, sidak, dunnettx
#Pre-planed: adjust='none'
#Post Hoc, all possible pair: adjust='tukey'
#an possible linear contrast: adjust='scheffe'
#an arbitrary set of c() comparision: adjust='bonferroni'
#differenct approximation like bonferroni: adjust='sidak'
#k active trt to 1 control trt comparision: adjust='dunnettx'

#Two way ANOVA: Type III F tests: 
joint_tests(diamonds.emm)
#pairwise dierences, Two groups are NOT signicantly dierent if same letter or number. 
#Tukey adjustment by default.
cld(diamonds.emm)
